tury bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":3,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Foliot was born in 1452, in Stanford on Teme, Worcestershire, England, his father, Sir Richard Foliot, was 21 and his mother, Johanna 'Joan' Verney, was 12. He married Elizabeth Washbourne about 1474, in Wichenford, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1504, in Pirton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1452–1504":"1452–1504","1452–1539":"1452–1539","1475–1545":"1475–1545","1495–1555":"1495–1555","1431–Male":"1431–Surnud","1440–1545":"1440–1545","1440":"1440","1495":"1495","10 January 1495":"10. jaanuar 1495","1545":"1545","1555":"1555","1455":"1455","Abt 1475":"umbes 1475","1431":"1431","1475":"1475","1452":"1452","about 1451":"umbes 1451","ab